04534nam a22005775i 9780774865739DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20212021xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748657397 a10.59962/97807748657392doi  a(DE-B1597)661070  a(OCoLC)1394872353  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 7aSOC0080202bisacsh04a610.73071/151qOCoLC223/eng/20231120  aNQ 57602rvk0(DE-625)rvk/128643:1 aGrypma, Sonya, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aNursing Shifts in Sichuan :bCanadian Missions and Wartime China, 1937–1951 /cSonya Grypma. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (320 p.) :b15 photos, 13 tables, 1 map, 1 chart  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tIllustrations and Tables -- tAbbreviations -- tHistorical Highlights -- tKey People -- tForeword -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- tBefore the Closure of the Peking Union Medical College -- tChina Calling (1914–33) -- tUnsettling Nursing (1932–40) -- tShifting Missions (1936–40) -- tWaiting to Exhale (1940–42) -- tAfter the Closure of the Peking Union Medical College -- tStarting Over in West China (1943–45) -- tFighting the Foundation’s “Darling Child” (1943–46) -- t“Our Triumphant Return” (1946–49) -- tThe Last Chapter (1949–51) -- tConclusion -- tAcknowledgments -- tList of Nurses at the West China Mission, 1895–1951 -- tPUMC Nursing Faculty, 1917–49 -- tList of Interned Nurses in China -- tPUMC Nursing Graduates, 1924–39 -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aNursing Shifts in Sichuan illuminates one of the most consequential additions to early-twentieth-century health care in China. In 1943, the Peking Union Medical College (PUMC) was forced to evacuate to the Canadian West China Mission in Chengdu, Sichuan. As part of an extraordinary mass migration to Free China during the Japanese occupation, the refugee PUMC was hosted by the Canadian West China Mission for the next three years. During that period, the PUMC transformed nursing at the Canadian mission, initiating the second university nursing program in the country. Both programs were closed by the new Communist government in 1951. When China reopened degree programs thirty-five years later, it was PUMC alumnae who helped restart them. In the contemporary era of exponential increases in East–West educational exchanges, Nursing Shifts in Sichuan offers both a cautionary tale about the fragility of transnational relations and a testament to the resilience of educated women.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMissions, MedicalzChinazSichuan ShengxHistoryy20th century. 0aNursingxStudy and teachingzChinaxHistoryy20th century. 0aNursingzChinaxHistoryy20th century. 0aSino-Japanese War, 1937-1945xRefugeeszChina. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Asian Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311127221408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2021z978311127464508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311141764640uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077486573940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774865739423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774865739/original  a978-3-11-127221-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  a978-3-11-127464-5  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2021b2021  a978-3-11-141764-6  University of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles